name: Paul Gerke
tweet: There was one black friend at the party that night. He ran through the woods behind my house rather than face the police. Back then, I just figured it was because he didn‚Äôt want an MIP (Minor in Possession). But it was so much more than that.

name: Paul Gerke
tweet: The police hid our keys in the yard so we couldn‚Äôt drive drunk. That was it. Then they left and our night was back to normal. I never realized how privileged I was to escape that night with my life, let alone a ticket for having a few Budweisers in my system.

name: Paul Gerke
tweet: We were all given breathalyzers. They took our information. One friend got put in a cop car because he was crying and verbally assaulting the officers while refusing to tell them his real name. But NONE of us were issued a citation, an MIP, or anything at all.

name: Paul Gerke
tweet: Cut to the chase, the police find the 6-10 of us who decided to hide. Yet, none of us (all white) were even verbally assaulted, much less physically. IT NEVER ENTERED MY MIND THAT POPPING OUT OF A DARK BATHROOM AND SURPRISING THE POLICE COULD BE DANGEROUS FOR ME.

name: Paul Gerke
tweet: The police came to the door and knocked loudly. My sister opened it and allowed them in. The police then walked through the dark house with flashlights, likely suspecting there were people hiding, but not knowing what to expect. I was curled up in the tub of a half bathroom.

name: Paul Gerke
tweet: Late in the night, someone called the cops. But a friend with a police scanner was able to tip us off. About half the party ran, some even driving through my backyard and into the woods. The rest of us, incredibly stupidly, turned off all the lights in the house and hid.

name: Paul Gerke
tweet: I was 16 years old. My folks were gone for the weekend, and I hosted a small party at my house. Maybe 15-20 people, sharing whatever crappy beer we could get our hands on. Loud music, swisher sweets, card games... Even a couple girls showed up, a banner achievement for HS me.

name: Paul Gerke
tweet: I grew up in mid-Michigan, in a predominantly white lower middle class suburb of Flint. Once you get out of the town itself, there‚Äôs a lot of backwoods-y dirt roads and open space. This allows for kids to do dumb things, like host parties when their parents are out of town.

name: Paul Gerke
tweet: The last week has made me think about my white privilege in ways I hadn‚Äôt considered before. I‚Äôd like to publicly share a story with you. It‚Äôs an example of how my skin color allowed me to escape a potentially dangerous situation with nothing but a story to laugh at.
